Predicting Housing Prices in Mecklenberg County, NC

Aidan Rhianne & Chris Michael

September 21, 2022

A. Introduction

The Purpose of Predicting Housing Prices

The residential housing market contributes to nearly 5% of the overall GDP in the U.S. With the ongoing ‘Pandemic Housing Boom’ and the rise in the number of homeowners in the country, market-place companies like Zillow rely on housing price prediction to drive real estate efficiency. Housing prices are directly related to the number of renters, home-owners, and overall economy of a place. Housing price prediction can help developers determine the selling price of homes, as well as help potential buyers plan out their purchase. Predicting home prices, however, is a multifaceted process that depends on:

i. physical conditions and characteristics of the structure (building materials, facades, architectural style etc.)
ii. location and context (site location, distance from urban amenities, transit etc.)
iii. the demographics of the neighborhood where it is located.

This projects aims to build a predictive model for home prices in Mecklenberg County, North Carolina. This model is loosely based on Zillow’s private estimate, but accounts for the local context, demographics and spatial distribution of urban amenities. Modelling housing prices not only helps plan for future development but also helps visualize how demographic variables like race and income disparities drive clustering of home prices in neighborhoods. This was a difficult exercise in terms of the amount and type of data that was available to us, and choosing which ones could be potential drivers of home prices. Our stratergy was to look at data that we assumed had an effect on where people chose to buy homes- within a well-rated school districts, near transit infrastructure etc.

The major drivers of home prices in Mecklenberg County seem to be internal characteristics of the home- like number of bedrooms, story height etc. We also noticed that proximity to parks and amenities like day care facilities also seemed to have an effect on sales prices. Our final model does have some significant error, which can potentially be attributed to extremely high/low home values that could be skewing the data. The model is, however, fairly generalizable for Mecklenberg County and does better at predicting sales prices of homes in high income areas. With future research, more comprehensive, rigorous version of this model could be recommended as a alternative to the Zillow Zestimate.

C. Talking about the Data

I. American Community Survey (2019)

We pulled data from the 2019 5-year American Community Survey (ACS) from the U.S Census Bureau. The selected geography includes the 233 tracts in Mecklenberg County, North Carolina. The variables we looked at were total population, median household income, and percent of population with a bachelors degree. We wanted to take a look at whether factors like income and education had an effect on housing prices in a locality, and the extent of its influence.

tracts19 <- 
  get_acs(geography = "tract", 
          variables = c("B01001_001E", "B19013_001E", "B15001_050E", "B15001_009E"), 
          year=2019, state=37, county=119, 
          geometry=TRUE, output="wide") %>%
  rename(TotalPop = B01001_001E,
         MedHHInc = B19013_001E,
         FBachelor = B15001_050E,
         MBachelor = B15001_009E) %>%
  dplyr::select(-NAME, -starts_with("B")) %>%
  mutate(pctBachelors = ifelse(TotalPop > 0, ((FBachelor + MBachelor) / TotalPop),0)) %>%
  dplyr::select(-FBachelor, -MBachelor, TotalPop)

II. Housing Data (Student Data)

The studentdata.geojson was interesting to look at, because it had variables that were most likely to affect housing prices. Some of the variables that we wanted to take a look at included the age of houses, the building grade, the number of amenities like bedrooms, bathrooms and fireplaces etc. We’ve also included two maps showing the location and age of homes for a quick visualization of the data. A mojorty of the homes are located in Charlotte, which is a majory commercial hub in NC. We can also see that a majority of these homes are around 60 years old, with newer homes being built as we move away from the center of the commercial district- which could be a nod to the growth of the suburbs in recent years.

III. Transit Data

Most of the transit data was collected from the Mecklenberg County Open Mapping website. We looked at light rail stations as well as bus stations, to observe how distance from transit influenced housing prices. We used the light rail stations to create TOD indicators, and looked at the number of bus stops within comfortable walking distance (1/2 mile) from a home. From the accompanying maps, we can see that a large portion of the county is serviced by public transit, with the exception of the suburbs. The newer homes in the region could imply that the development was not transit oriented.

We split the final dataset into the modelling and the challenge dataset. We also divided the modelling dataset on two- a training set; on which we would create our statistical prediction models, and a test set; on which we would test our models.

MKLB_modelling<- MKLB %>% filter(toPredict=="MODELLING")
MKLB_challenge <-MKLB %>% filter(toPredict=="CHALLENGE")

The map shows the dependent variable- sales price and the range of its values across the county. It can be observed that a larger portion of the more expensive homes are located in Charlotte- the commercial center, with a few scattered in the northern part of the county. At this stage, it is difficult to talk about what the cause of this distribution might be- but it could be due to higher income residents, who are willing to pay to be close to the urban center and near transit infrastructure.

III. Visualizing Independent Variables

This section has a few visualizations of some independent variables that we thought were interested to look at like the presence of green open spaces around homes and the median household income of the area. We wanted to note the higher number of public parks near the urban center, with fewer designated ‘public’ green spaces as we moved further into the suburbs. It is also interesting to see that a larger portion of wealthier residents seem to be moving into the suburbs as well.

II. Goodness of Fit

We created four new columns in test set, namely predicted sales price (using the training model), the error in sales price, the mean absolute error in sales price, and the absolute percent error in sales price (this is the difference between predicted and observed prices on a percentage basis). We also removed outlier homes with a sales price that was exceedingly high and could potentially skew our model.

Testing for goodness of fit, we can see that the Mean Sales Price of Homes is $456342.2. The Mean Average Error is 126202.5, which is not trivial. The overall Mean Absolute Percentage Error is 25%, as shown in the table below.

MKLB_test <-
  MKLB_test %>%
  mutate(SalePrice.Predict = predict(reg1, MKLB_test),
         SalePrice.Error = SalePrice.Predict - price,
         SalePrice.AbsError = abs(SalePrice.Predict - price), 
         SalePrice.APE = (abs(SalePrice.Predict - price)) / SalePrice.Predict)%>%
  filter(price < 5000000)

MKLB_test.table <- data.frame(NAME='Mecklenberg Test Data Set',
   MAE = mean(na.omit(MKLB_test$SalePrice.AbsError)),
   MAPE = mean(na.omit(MKLB_test$SalePrice.APE)))
MKLB_test.table %>% kable() %>% kable_styling()
NAME MAE MAPE
Mecklenberg Test Data Set 126202.5 0.2501864



III. Cross Validation

Cross Validation is a way to test generalizability of the model (using k-fold of 100). The mean we obtain for all 100 MAE observations, should be exactly the same as the average MAE shown above. If the model is generalizable to new data, we should expect comparable goodness of fit metrics across each fold.

The Mean Average Error across each fold is 126875.1, which is close to our obtained MAE of 126202.5. This implies that our model would be fairly generalizable across the county, for the purpose of this analysis.

fitControl <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 100)
set.seed(825)

reg.cv <- 
  train(price ~ ., data = 
          st_drop_geometry(MKLB_modelling) %>% 
          dplyr::select(price, BldAge, heatedarea, BldStry,Fuel, 
                        numfirepla, fullbaths, halfbaths,bedrooms, units, 
                        BldGrd, shape_Area, ParkBuffer, BusStopBuffer,
                        ExtWall, totalac,shape_Leng,Lib_nn1, 
                        Lib_nn2, Lib_nn3, Lib_nn3, Lib_nn4,
                        Lib_nn5,daycare_nn1, daycare_nn2,daycare_nn3,
                        daycare_nn4, daycare_nn5,TOD, TotalPop, MedHHInc,
                        pctBachelors,School_nn1, School_nn2, School_nn3, 
                        School_nn4, School_nn5, WasteBuffer,HUNTERSVILLE, 
                        CORNELIUS, DAVIDSON, CHARLOTTE,MINTHILL, 
                        MATTHEWS, PINEVILLE), 
     method = "lm", trControl = fitControl, na.action = na.pass)

MKLB_cross.table <- data.frame(NAME='Cross Validation Data',
   MAE = mean(na.omit(reg.cv$resample$MAE)))
MKLB_cross.table %>% kable() %>% kable_styling()
NAME MAE
Cross Validation Data 126875.1

In terms of generalizibility, it shows afair amount of generalizability and we believe our model would still be a good option for the purpose of our study.

barplot(reg.cv$resample$MAE,col="#dc863b",border="#dc863b",

IV. Understanding Auto Spatial Correlation

In this section, we attempt to understand Auto Spatial correlation (relationships within space- spatial lag, k-nearest-neighbor, and distance vs variables of our choice). The first plot of price as a function of spatial lag price implies that as price increases, so does the price of nearby houses. The correlation for this spatial lag relationship is 0.82 and is highly statistically significant. This is substantial evidence for clustering of home prices. The second plot shows home price error as function of spatial lag error. It imply that as home price errors increase, so does nearby home price errors.

MKLB_modelling1 <-
  MKLB_modelling %>%
  mutate(Regression = "Final Regression",
         SalePrice.Predict = predict(reg1, MKLB_modelling),
         SalePrice.Error = price - SalePrice.Predict,
         SalePrice.AbsError = abs(price - SalePrice.Predict),
         SalePrice.APE = (abs(price - SalePrice.Predict)) / price)%>%
  filter(price < 5000000)

coords <- st_coordinates(MKLB_modelling1) 
neighborList <- knn2nb(knearneigh(coords, 5))
spatialWeights <- nb2listw(neighborList, style="W")
MKLB_modelling1$lagPrice <- lag.listw(spatialWeights, MKLB_modelling1$price)

MKLB_modelling1$lagPriceError <- lag.listw(spatialWeights, MKLB_modelling1$SalePrice.AbsError, NAOK = TRUE)

CO <- ggplot(MKLB_modelling1, aes(x=lagPrice, y=price)) +
    geom_point(size=2, shape=20, color = "#899da4", alpha=0.5) +
    geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, colour = "#b94d36") +
    labs(title = "Price as a function of the Spatial Lag of Price",
         subtitle = "Correlation Coefficient: 0.822",
         x = "Spatial Lag of Price (Mean Price of 5 Nearest Neighbors)",
         y = "Sales Price") +
    theme_minimal()

DO <- ggplot(MKLB_modelling1, aes(x=lagPriceError, y=price)) +
    geom_point(size=2, shape=20, color = "#899da4", alpha=0.5) +
    geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, colour = "#b94d36") +
    labs(title = "Error as a function of the Spatial Lag of Price",
         subtitle = "Correlation Coefficient: 0.822",
         x = "Spatial Lag of Errors (Mean Error of 5 Nearest Neighbors)",
         y = "Sales Price Error") +
  theme_minimal()

ggarrange(CO,DO,align = "v")



V. Morans I Test

The Moran’s I statistic is 0.32, which implies some positive spatial autocorrelation, or clustering. Moreover, we have a p-value around 0.001 suggesting that our model errors cluster more than what we might expect due to random chance alone, again suggesting spatial correlation in our modelling dataset.

moranTest <- moran.mc(MKLB_modelling1$SalePrice.AbsError, 
                      spatialWeights, nsim = 999, na.action = na.exclude)

ggplot(as.data.frame(moranTest$res[c(1:999)]), aes(moranTest$res[c(1:999)])) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.01) +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = moranTest$statistic), colour = "#dc863b",size=1) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(-1, 1)) +
  labs(title="Observed and Permuted Moran's I",
       subtitle= "Moran's I Statistic: 0.32 \nObserved Moran's I in orange",
       x="Moran's I",
       y="Count") +
  theme_minimal()

G. Understanding Neighborhood Fixed Effects

I. MAPE by Neighborhood

We can see that there are rich homes skewing data- as we plot the mean average percent error (MAPE) as a function of price, homes with low sales prices have high errors. This implies that our model predicts well for certain areas, namely those in higher income neighborhoods.

Zip_Summary <- MKLB_test %>%
    group_by(zipcode) %>%
    summarize(meanPrice = mean(price, na.rm = T),
       meanPredict = mean(SalePrice.Predict, na.rm = T),
       meanPriceError = mean(SalePrice.Error, na.rm = T),
       meanPriceAbsError = mean(SalePrice.AbsError, na.rm = T),
       meanPriceAPE = mean(SalePrice.APE, na.rm = T)) 

ggplot(Zip_Summary) +
  geom_point(aes(meanPrice, meanPriceAPE),size=2.5, shape=20, 
             color = "#899da4", alpha=0.6) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", aes(meanPrice, meanPriceAPE), 
              se = FALSE, colour = "#b94d36")+
  labs(title = "MAPE as a function of Mean Price (by Zipcode)",
       subtitle = "Mecklenberg County, NC\n",
       x = "Mean Home Price", y = "MAPE",
       caption = "Figure 7.5") +
  theme_minimal()



Taking a look at the MAPE as a function of Mean Price scatterplot: Generally this looks good, there is a very low error by mean home price across most zipcodes, but there are a couple of low price homes that seem to have very high errors when predicting their sale price. Given the map below, these homes seem likely to be located in areas of low income.

II. Variables from the Census

Using tidycensus, we split the model into two- based on race and income to observe the spatial variations in price based on these variables.

tracts19_A <- 
  get_acs(geography = "tract", variables = c("B01001_001E","B01001A_001E","B06011_001E"), 
          year = 2019, state=37, county=119, geometry=T, output = "wide") %>%
  st_transform('EPSG:2264')  %>%
  rename(TotalPop = B01001_001E,
         NumberWhites = B01001A_001E,
         Median_Income = B06011_001E) %>%
  mutate(percentWhite = NumberWhites / TotalPop,
         raceContext = ifelse(percentWhite > .5, "Majority White", "Majority Non-White"),
         incomeContext = ifelse(Median_Income > 38437, "High Income", "Low Income"))

Y <- ggplot() + geom_sf(data = na.omit(tracts19_A), aes(fill = raceContext)) +
    scale_fill_manual(values = c("#a9685b", "#faefd1"), name="Race Context") +
    labs(title = "Race Context",
         subtitle = "Mecklenberg County, NC\n",
         caption = "\nSource: Student Data") +
    theme_void()

Z <- ggplot() + geom_sf(data = na.omit(tracts19_A), aes(fill = incomeContext)) +
    scale_fill_manual(values = c("#899da4", "#dc863b"), name="Income Context") +
    labs(title = "Income Context",
         subtitle = "Mecklenberg County, NC\n",
         caption = "\nSource: Student Data") +
    theme_void()

ggarrange(Y,Z, align = "v")



Comparing the maps above with our tables- our model appears biased, given that it works better on predicting sales prices in zipcodes where there is a majority white population. The higher 35% MAPE for majority non-white, suggests our model doesn’t generalize well across these neigborhoods.

Taking a look at the income related variations- the MAPE is 28% for high-income and 36% for lower-income. This implies that our model does better at predicting house sale prices in high income areas. This is an expected observation given that the previous maps show that race and income are related.

H. Discussions

Overall, this model is a good place to start building upon. Despite the fair amount of generalizability, we do not think this is an effective model as it does not do well when it comes to predicting home prices in low-income, predominately non-white neighborhoods. This is an important especially when taking the racial and income discrepancies all over the country. Our model does have the potential to be better fitted, provided we take more demographic and spatial variables into consideration. Places of work, commute times, grocery stores and even nearby water bodies have an effect on sales prices.

Some of the more interesting variables in our study were the presence of parks and public open spaces around homes. Publicly accessible green space has become an important part of residential living- particularly after the pandemic, so it was interesting to look at how this spatial variable affected sales price. To touch briefly on the prediction error- our model had an error of 25%, and was able to predict home sales prices in high income neighborhoods fairly well. As mentioned previously, the lack of more information (both economic and demographic), meant that our model predicted poorly in certain regions of the county.

I. Conclusions

  • Pulling from ACS, housing, and open data we created a model to predict sales prices in Mecklenberg County, NC
  • We observed a low error of 25% in our model (this is the difference between predicted and observed prices). With this low value we can say that our model is pretty accurate!)
  • The model generalizes fairly well, but does better at predicting house sale prices in high income areas, indicating a bias
  • Geographical location also seems to have an effect on our model, i.e model works better in high income tracts (closer to the urban center and to the north of the county), and poorly in low-income tracts.
  • We would recommend our model to Zillow, but with a caveat that it should not be used on areas of low income (e.g. areas with income < 38437) because the error is much too high to be useful.
  • We could improve this model by adding spatial variables like proximity to hospitals, shopping centers and cafes, as well as looking at demographical variables like age and rate of household formation.
